Author: @Brandon_m2507
Comment:
Limbo, what it really represents...my view

No it doesn't not represent death or original sin. It's human nature and the evolution of humanity.

Progressively, we see the natural environment evolve.


In the beginning we see lots of basic technology and savages with arrows obviously representing the dawn of humanity.

Our only threat is nature which is then killed by us...pretty symbolic and on the nose with the spider. The spider is oversized, almost mutated by nuclear radiation.

But then we start to see more and more buildings and more and more industrialised sections as time goes on. We're beginning to return to normalcy.

Then we introduce electricity to the mix. The desire for human progress is evident. It's all chronological with the evolution of man.

Then we get to the militarised sections. The background is modern too, there's a tire and more stuff when we first meet anti gravity.

But the anti gravity really symbolises the advancements in technology. This doesn't yet exist.

The breaking of the glass at the end and how we end up in the same place as where we started shows the futility of progress. We just repeat the same pattern over and over again, starting out as savages with nature to fear every time we have a disaster. The consequences of a third world war/nuclear disaster which is why lots of trees and buildings are abandoned and destroyed.

Tldr:
Nuclear disaster/too much progress destroys humanity, doomed to repeat the same cycle by continuing to break the glass.

Author: @christophernoluyolan9687
Comment:
Here is my theory blending multiple existing theories: it was the time when WWII broke out (That's why, everywhere is isolated and abandoned) and our children are the victims (maybe Jewish idk)(That's why he is chased by other children everywhere). 
After being hit by a bomb, their treehouse collapses and they both dies. Both goes to limbo state and try to find each other in a familiar place (treehouse) in this nightmare. Treehouse is most probably a representation of heaven because it mean so much to them in their mind.
The girl reaches their treehouse long before her brother and waits him there hopelessly. As the boy we share the same aim and throughout the pilgrimage, we try to flee from our fears which derives from our past life (such as boys as bullies, spiders, dark, drowning, factories manufacturing weapons for war). 
Before the end we shatter the glass and I think this a metaphor of breaking the cycle and breaking free from our limbo state and reach the heaven. After waking up, we reach our sister and our heaven. Just before we arrive our sister gives up and bury us as a remembrance (that's why at the end we see her burying something and gets spooked when she feels our existence behind her).

Author: @kennygreen4393
Comment:
I just remembered something... For those of you that are familiar with the old school classic animated show "Ed, Edd n Eddy", there's a dark truth behind every one of the cul-de-sac kids (except the Kankers sisters) present in the animated show... What I really wanna reveal is something that relates to two of the characters namely Ed & Sarah and the little boy & girl of this game.

First of all, the cul-de-sac which is known as Peach Creek is revealed to be a purgatory that is inhabited by the souls of the kids that died in real life from different timeline typically in the early to mid 20th(1900s) century and in this purgatory, neither of the kids can recollect their past life memories which also further adds to why there aren't adult characters in the show. 

Secondly, Ed and his little sister Sarah who were the souls of the siblings that died in the same car accident in the year 1953 and that's quite similar to the timeline of the little boy and his sister in this Limbo game. Another key thing is Ed and the Limbo boy share the same traits as protective or rather caring brother over their little sister they deemed helpless which was also the same as the boy and the girl they depicted.

Author: @TheChej
Comment: Lets start with the menu of the game. The flies. The flies over the rotting corpses ( possibly the brother and sister), represents reality, the real world. The old tree house and its broken parts. Brother and sister fell out of the tree house to their deaths. That is what really happened go yhe main character and his sister. Now for the gameplay itself.  The gameplay is nothing but obstacles of negative memories and fears the boy had while alive. Like the fear of spiders, and bullies. The many deaths in the game represents the very meaning of being in limbo. He is trying to get to heaven, and i believe heaven for him is reuniting with his sister. Eventually,  he get through his obstacles, his fears, the gameplay for the player. He gets through his own rendition of limbo by breaking through another barrier (the glass he breaks through) in the afterlife and reaches heaven,  his sister. Im sure his sister had her own limbo before reaching the treehouse. And look at WHERE they both end up at. The treehouse, their resting place. The place they both died.

Author: @Philandhisdog
Comment: Its pretty easy to understand. Its based on dantes inferno but its arnt (the creator of limbo) personal hell & the boy is a representation of himself in it. The factory could be his past employment where he hated it, the rain could represent depression, the gravity could represent his moods, the guns could represent his anger/violent outburst & the glass is him accepting his life & how it turned out. His "sister" could represent purgatory or a rebirth into a different lifestyle allowing him to leave limbo (leave behind his old life). All the death that happens are all arnts fault through his actions. Perhaps he knew in his life if he reacted to an event or emotion in that way, that would be the price to pay. So in real life he'd kill whatever he was doing but in the game it actually kills you. Why did all this happen? Simple, a troubled man & his emotions becoming lost in life (the woods in this representation) & this is he personal journey to redeem himself. So of like the "hero's journey" by joesph Campbell.

Comment: I originally believed him and his sister both were in real world but souls got taken to there own form of limbo and they just need to return to our world and they would still be alive but I do not think this anymore. I believe he is dead ,and going from a sort of Christian perspective but we will slightly tweak it as it is a game, I believe he has slipped from purgatory and fallen to limbo, you see in our belief Purgatory is one the happiest things you can go through (heaven is top obviously) and the reason being is that you first are judged and if in purgatory that means you are going to heaven as purgatory is where your sins are forgiven and you are made pure, sure purgatory is also called the most painful (but not as much as hell) stage but it is the happiest as you know you have been accepted to be in heaven. So he is dead but maybe he is not quite ready to got to purgatory and things need to be resolved and thatâ€™s where limbo comes in (I will be going off Christian belief as it is a game and it will have changed it slightly) so basically limbo is just a state of solving things that happened in his life and bringing understanding to him, with the fears you mentioned I think you did it well but the only thing I want to add is along with the hotel I also think at the factory area he might have seen a death or it could be as you said he was just put in another terrifying situation, basically he was too young to get his understanding of these fears and limbo was a way of teaching him. The ending as you said is still debated which I if I am being honest I like. Oh and one more thing, for Catholics specifically although never mentioned I found out that limbo also is this: In Catholic theology, Limbo (Latin: limbus, 'edge' or 'boundary', referring to the edge of Hell) is the afterlife condition of those who die in original sin without being assigned to the Hell of the Damned, so I think it also links to the one you mentioned about not being baptised or given chance to prove yourself so you die and need to prove yourself through limbo but as seen he did not die before birth as he is a young boy butâ€¦                 Maybe he did die before birth or just was born and the young boy we see is just how he is represented (his avatar if thatâ€™s how you would like to think of it) and all those fears he encounters are not his really as he did not experience them or have the chance to fear them but actually are the symbols for the fears of mankind, the classic spiders, drowning in deep waters - the unknown, people hurting other people - moral suffering, the machinery/factory representing humans destructive creations (weapons for battle/war, machinery to torture or the fear of the world being corrupted by this) now the factory area could also represent when it comes to creation, the creation of sin, that is probably a hidden meaning behind all the creation stuff. Now this is all just a bunch of theories so they could be almost completely wrong but it is still nice to theorise, I hope you could maybe do another short video including new theories on limbo and inside, I have played limbo and I have inside and have not played it yet but I will soon.

Some Observations:
*Pugatory would be more religiously fitting, but Limbo is also a Jameican Sport requiring agility so it may be intentional ambigious
*The Boat in the beginning might reference Charon
*Feral Children are featured in Lord of the Flies. Literal Flies are a recuring theme in Limbo, too.
*The Spider might have a deeper meaning than Arachnophobia. Webs are often a Symbol of Decay.

Author: @nedim_guitar
Comment:
I bought this game a few years ago, I played it for the first time last year for a few days, and today I finished it. I didn't know I only had four chapters left, it didn't take more than 10-15 minutes. Anyway... The third theory, that he is a spirit and she is alive and burying him could be a valid theory. She doesn't even have white glowing eyes. Then again, why did she bury him with her bare hands? And where are the parents? Maybe she spent her time in limbo burying him, while he went through this whole insane and traumatic adventure, while her burying her brother with her bare hands is traumatic for her. The car crash theory doesn't have much of anything to support it, except for chaning gravity. The crumbling hotel could be a place where they visited as a family, but since this is the afterlife, everything is in ruins. Alternatively, maybe everything was destroyed in a war, including the lives of him and his family, but that could be a bit far fetched. It's likely that they were two lost souls that needed to find each other to move on. 

There are still some questions, though. Who died by hanging? Who died by drowning? What mark did that leave? 

The game is very well done. Fun and challenging, a litlte spooky. And the mystery just makes it stick around in your brain for longer.

Comment:
i have a little bit of a theory, instead of the protagonist dying as a child its the opposite, 
we start out at the forest, where a baby boy was born, peacefully living out his days, one day while he was exploring he found a girl his age and they decided to build a tree house together, over time he came to love the girl and the time spent with her were the happiest days of his life, unfortunantly one time they were playing the girl tripped on the ladder and fell to her death, the boy could only watch in horror as her life left her body, he buried her under the tree house they shared, traumatised by her death the boy became reclusive and as such the other children in his town (the tribe of kids) began to pick on him and belittle him.
when he became a teenager he decided to leave the town which held awful memories and move to the city, he got a job as a factory worker (the place with the gears) and was content, however soon after he settled in the second world war happened and the boy decided he was destined for glory so he signed up (introduction of guns).
long after the war the scars of the boy never left his mind, he percieved everything in horrifying ways and had turned to alcohol and drugs to escape from reality (gravity bending area).
the boy died driving while his brain was muddled my drugs, his body flew out the car (final glass bit) and he drew his final breath.
im his limbo he is forced to relive his painfull life over and over again to try make it back to his child hood, to his happiest days, to the girl.

Author: @neptunianmoon6285
Comment:
I think both siblings died in a car crash and they entered their own limbo trying to discover each other's fate. The treehouse is their meeting place, perhaps they had a pact "If we get lost, we meet at the treehouse". Because they're both dead, the treehouse fell into disarray from lack of use. The girl reaches it first through her own limbo journey and waits there. When the boy arrives, they can finally both be at peace, and their graves are side by side under the treehouse. 

The only thing I'm wondering is whether their cause of death might be war-related, instead of a car crash, which would make sense given the guns and factories in the game. Maybe an explosion from a bomb.

XXXTENTACION reunites with Killstation of his Members Only collective on â€œLIMBO.â€ The two artists talk about their regrets and how they are stuck alone in their heads, or their own limbos, where they seem to be caught between two stages and it is unclear what will happen next. Killstation reflects on Xâ€™s passing and details how it has affected his mental state. For example, he has to remind himself that X is gone or he would otherwise pretend that he isnâ€™t. Killstatonâ€™s contributions to the song are reminiscent of several tracks on Members Onlyâ€™s January 2019 album, Members Only, Vol. 4. On â€œNothing,â€ Killstation, Craig Xen, and Cooliecut sing about their numbness and inner turmoil as a result of Xâ€™s passing. In his verse, Killstation sings:

"I donâ€™t feel right, losin' my mind
I see you all the time only when I shut my eyes".

On â€œCold Weather,â€ the same trio reflects on Xâ€™s death, emphasizing how his tragic death has caused them to become alone and cold. In his verse, Killstation sings:

"Time and time again, Iâ€™m all alone
Iâ€™m always lookin' for you
Why do I pretend that Iâ€™m not cold?
Iâ€™m always lookin' for you".

â€œLIMBOâ€ was originally solely Killstationâ€™s song and was intended to appear on Members Only, Vol. 4. It could have very likely been made around the same time as â€œNothingâ€ and â€œCold Weather,â€ as indicated by their common themes. X reflects on his past actions that led him to drown in his own regrets. He was constantly going in and out of jails, while also dealing with relationship issues. It made him feel as if the pain would never end, and all he could do is pretend.

Author: @lastii3668
Comment:
As a Fellow Limbo Main and a so-called by my clan Limbo-fucker (that sounds better in my native language) with 21 builds on him, I agree with most of the material about the way it works. Obviously, not every build is the same and I have a rule not to take and not to model myself on other builds because I won't learn anything myself

The Limbo rework has been rumbling in the community for quite some time now
And people usually ask more for a change of guard so that CC affects them even in reduced strength than the Limbo rework itself
Why? Because it will benefit more frames like Gyre, Vauban, Koumei etc.
Especially when the community, especially the older one, unfortunately has the opinion that Limbo is a troll and it's better not to play with him - which changed a bit after Scarlet Spear and the return of Hieracon as an Axi farm for some time (until Lua disruption appeared and people didn't want to go to Kal-Azar)
I'm not saying that it's good to change the overguard effect but it's something that comes up most often (or rather from what I see in posts on Reddit/X) than the hatter himself because since few people play him anyway, he's a troll because he pushes everyone into the void but has high damage but only him so it's better for the team to be tailored to him and not him to them so... people won't want to do it
I'll go briefly on the subject of Warframe design. Unfortunately, Dante is not the best example - in my opinion.

People like simplicity, especially if it does a lot of damage (Ex. Saryn with a build for Sobek and Roar) or if they are immortal (Wukong/Revenant). And honestly, the statistics of recent years show this tendency and as usual, new Frames don't even exceed 4/10% of usability because the rest is distributed among the previously mentioned 3. You can add Mesa as an example of survivability, damage and map clearing aka Nuke. Dante was a answer to this, to find a frame that is easy to get, easy to build and does damage, nuke and survivability. They did it in an exaggerated way but probably definitely not in such a way that it is the fault of the so-called Doritos.
Yes, I know that Wukong and Revenant don't do everything that Dante does, but Saryn can if you give her Breach Surge instead of Molta, which gives CC=survivability+damage, or Mesa, which has practically everything.
And the new frames have different tendencies, an example of which is Qorvex, and even better is Jade or Cyte.
The rework issues are different because it depends on the point of view. Hydroid lost the puddle aka its trademark, but it doesn't take away from the fact that now it does more than throw tentacles for a double drop. Grendel is a ball that each of us will be after a kebab, but he is durable, has one of the best buffs, two armor strips (sic!) and damage that can be raised higher with augment to 4.
A bigger problem are bandaids like the aforementioned Gyre - Augment is so mandatory that it must always be there because without it the frame sucks

Author: @EmptyTenementSpirit
Comment:
I have to admit, while I almost... completely disagree with your assessment of Warframe kit design as being an abomination because of the direction it went in, I pretty much agree with everything else.

Limbo has been great - outside of his issues - for a long time, and the greater Warframe community simply doesn't want to actually tap into his potential, which is fair, I can appreciate that he isn't a frame for everybody, but he's far from bad. I've also spent years just accepting that it's a lost battle to try and convince other people that he's actually good, much like some other frames who have always had high potential locked behind required effort.

Generally, I don't think CC is bad or has ever actually been bad, even WITH Eximus Overguard. Fact of the matter to me is that these enemies are still not really a problem, and if anything, with the newly buffed magnetic and secondary fortifier can be tools for you as a player to keep yourself alive more. I frankly don't care if my CC affects them or not when they have Overguard, because I can just kill them? Or reduce their Overguard so it does affect them? Or take their Overguard for my own.

Warframe is a game where you can basically do whatever you want with whatever stuff you want, and I do find it funny that so many people hit a roadblock with Limbo specifically and assume he's bad just because he's complicated. For the record, my favourite frames overall range drastically in effort required, Saryn, Kullervo, Limbo, Dante and Revenant/Nova (put together because they fulfil the same "comfy do basically everything" role to me) are not exactly all in the same tier of difficulty, but I don't care because I like them for what they do.

Author: @just_d3spairity
Comment:
1:06:11 incorrect. That is the 700% stealth damage multiplier, which is a flat additive multiplier that applies at the same time as crits and shows up as the same yellow effect as crits to the number. This multiplier is only influenced by the rank of the weapon, where an unranked weapon has only +100% damage and it rises with weapon rank. Should you have continued whacking the ancient enough times with the timing delay, you would have seen the damage occasionally have spiked from hitting them and getting a normal crit and that bonus.
This is amittedly irrelevant to the point you were making, as the fact this damage stacks with crits without the AI changing thanks to Stasis maintaining that state is True, just that the reason the damage rises is incorrect.
Fun fact: you can blame Loki for this. Originally they'd blitz through missions with stuff like Maiming Strike Atterax or Heavy Attack Galatine better than the melee intended frames, so they slapped the stealth multiplier speed of application to bring him more in line with the others. This occurred in update 19.6.3, on January 17th 2017

2. Stasis: Instead of stopping enemy movement, boost you and allies' speed inside the rift. This speed increase is universal which means it also speeds up stuff like projectile spd, cast speed, etc.
3. Rift Surge: Hold to detonate all riftbound enemies and knock them out of rift. Explosion from surged enemies and/or enemies inside Cataclysm deal extra dmg. 4. Cataclysm: Instead of shrinking, your rift starts small and expands.

(Now that i've typed this all out, i realized this idea pretty much steals Equinox's gimmick XD)

Author: @arkhamcreed4326
Comment:
I just started experimenting with Limbo, and I love the concept. But there are a few things Iâ€™d like to see added or changed. One is a baseline thing but would probably be insanely overpowered. The other two ideas could be augment mods for Rift Surge.

Base Change: Limbo is invisible when ALONE in the rift and not in combat. That will let him just walk through spy missions or get into position, but the second he pulls an enemy into the rift to initiate combat he becomes visible across the rift again. Likewise, any ongoing source of damage Limbo or his enemies suffer will keep him visible for the duration.

Mod One: Instead of spreading Rift Surge to other enemies and forcing them into the rift, this mod would make Rift Surge do void damage in an AOE around any enemies ejected from the rift. This is a little more complex than being a fire-and-forget nuke however. First you have to pull enemies into the rift to prime them with Surge to begin with, the effect doesnâ€™t apply when the enemy dies within the rift, and it scales based on the number of affected enemies. So, youâ€™d still need to employ strategy and positioning to get the most out of it.

Mod Two: Cross Dimensional damage to surged targets. Once again, this disables Rift Surge being able to force targets back into the rift, so you can banish enemies, prime them with surge, and then eject them from the rift to maintain your own safety. The benefit here is any enemies affected by the new Rift Surge debuff this mod applies can be damaged by Limbo and his allies across dimensions. So, you could banish a group of enemies, surge them, then eject them from the rift where they cannot damage you, but where you can now damage them. In squad play this eliminates the dimension issue for your allies, as even if you keep enemies in the rift to lock them down with stasis your allies can still attack them through the rift so long as Rift Surge is active.

Author: @mindcap.
Comment:
I remember giving you the layout for this level to play as a joke, you weren't even a playtester for the level or anything, but as time passed, your love and dedication towards LIMBO had managed to surprise me and eventually the verification made it's way in your hands. At first, I was reluctant. I feared that someone who's hardest was a top 20-30 now wouldn't be qualify to beat a level like this. A lot of people told me to do so, a lot of others told me to give the level to someone else and finish it quicker, but you managed to stamp your name onto it as yours and only yours to finish. 

Your perseverance proved to be against all odds. This level would have come out quicker if I did give it to someone else that's true, but I'm sure I wouldn't have had much fun watching another guy play it. Your character and optimism are inspirational, in calls you'd be cheering up my and everyone else's day with your sense of humor while keeping all the pressure and pain to yourself, and that's truly an act of someone who only wants to see everyone happy. 

Fact of the matter is that I will remember this little level made in a videogame when I'm well over my 60s, it was just that memorable. When you got 90% again that day, I felt hopeless, and I'm usually never like that, I would be the one cheering you up, I thought you'd eventually break and leave the level again for months, and as the curse goes with any my level verifications, you did it when I was asleep, the only time I decided to go to bed. You did it an hour later, because you believed that it was not over yet.

You managed to prove everyone wrong, and even beat it on a refresh rate no one dares try a top 10 on. I believe this is the best project me and many others have worked on since the beginning of me playing this game, and I believe this is the best choice of verifier. GG Cooper 
â¤
